{"type":"assistant.message","data":{"messageId":"2ce0caa8-49db-4bf7-8ba8-3977842bb80e","content":"Use **dotnet-trace** — it's the easiest option for .NET apps and doesn't require installing Visual Studio or PerfView.\n\n### Quick steps:\n\n```powershell\n# 1. Install the tool (one-time)\ndotnet tool install --global dotnet-trace\n\n# 2. Find your process ID\ndotnet-trace ps\n\n# 3. Collect a CPU profile (30 seconds)\ndotnet-trace collect -p <PID> --profile cpu-sampling --duration 00:00:30 -o trace.nettrace\n```\n\n### Analyzing the trace:\n- **Windows**: Open `trace.nettrace` in Visual Studio (Diagnostics Hub) or PerfView.\n- **Cross-platform**: Convert to Speedscope format:\n  ```powershell\n  dotnet-trace convert trace.nettrace --format Speedscope\n  ```\n  Then open at [speedscope.app](https://www.speedscope.app).\n\n### Alternatives worth knowing:\n| Tool | When to use |\n|---|---|\n| **PerfView** | Deeper OS-level analysis (GC, kernel events) |\n| **dotnet-counters** | Quick live check before tracing (`dotnet-counters monitor -p <PID>`) |\n| **WPR/WPA** | Full system-wide ETW tracing |\n\n**Tip**: Run `dotnet-counters monitor -p <PID>` first to confirm it's actual CPU and not threadpool starvation or GC pressure before collecting a full trace.","toolRequests":[],"interactionId":"bcf70a34-cafd-4f02-ba28-3fd84413140a","reasoningOpaque":"","reasoningText":"The user is asking for guidance on collecting a CPU trace for a .NET 8 service on Windows Server. This is a knowledge question, not a code task. I can answer directly.","outputTokens":421},"id":"c4c6817d-f8c5-4a9d-a410-c9fc02b42661","timestamp":"2026-04-04T00:45:43.954Z","parentId":"ad77829b-5655-4dc0-a025-bc642ca235f8"}
